    <h1>Who is China&#x2019;s pick: Trump or Bi&#xAD;den?</h1>
    <h2>Is it to lure Bi&#xAD;den into a &#x2018;China hawk trap&#x2019;? Or is there not much dif&#xAD;fer&#xAD;ence re&#xAD;ally be&#xAD;tween the two can&#xAD;di&#xAD;dates on China?</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200830/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-30"><time>2020-08-30</time></a>
        - <span>FRONT PAGE</span>
        - <span role="byline">Nir&#xAD;mal Ghosh US Bureau Chief In Wash&#xAD;ing&#xAD;ton</span>
    </section>

    <p>The cam­paign to re-elect Pres­i­dent Donald Trump is cast­ing former vice-pres­i­dent Joe Bi­den as weak on China, tar­ring him with, among other nick­names, “Bei­jing Bi­den”.</p>
    <p>“China would own our coun­try if Joe Bi­den got elected,” Mr Trump said at a glit­ter­ing event at the White House last Thurs­day night to for­mally ac­cept the nom­i­na­tion of the Repub­li­can Party.</p>
    <p>“Bi­den is still shilling for the Chi­nese govern­ment to this day,” a Trump cam­paign e-mail said last Wednes­day. “Last year he told Amer­i­cans ‘they’re not bad folks, folks’.”</p>
    <p>A young sen­a­tor Joe Bi­den was part of the first United States del­e­ga­tion to visit Bei­jing fol­low­ing diplo­matic nor­mal­i­sa­tion in 1979.</p>
    <p>Af­ter the Cold War, he sup­ported China’s ac­ces­sion to the World Trade Or­gan­i­sa­tion, and as vi­cepres­i­dent, he echoed the view of the day – that the rise of China was a pos­i­tive de­vel­op­ment.</p>
    <p>The Trump cam­paign has also ac­cused Mr Bi­den’s son, Hunter, of per­son­ally prof­it­ing from his fa­ther’s friendly re­la­tion­ship with Chi­nese elites. It cites an ac­count that some time in 2011 or 2012, then Vice-Pres­i­dent Joe Bi­den re­port­edly told China leader Xi Jin­ping – be­fore the lat­ter be­came pres­i­dent – that Amer­i­can lead­ers sup­port hu­man rights only for the sake of po­lit­i­cal op­tics.</p>
    <p>Mr Trump him­self is not in­su­lated from crit­i­cism on the China front. His tout­ing of his spe­cial friend­ship with Pres­i­dent Xi did not pre­vent a pre­cip­i­tous de­te­ri­o­ra­tion in the re­la­tion­ship. “Trump gave Xi a green light both to crack down on Hong Kong’s po­lit­i­cal au­ton­omy and con­tinue with in­tern­ment camps for Mus­lim Uighurs in Xin­jiang – two is­sues that catal­ysed the re­cent sanc­tions and that the ad­min­is­tra­tion rou­tinely ad­ver­tises as proof of China’s vil­lainy,” Dr Van Jack­son, pro­fes­sor of in­ter­na­tional re­la­tions at Vic­to­ria Univer­sity in Welling­ton, New Zealand, wrote in For­eign Pol­icy mag­a­zine on Aug 13.</p>
    <p>Cer­tainly, in a coun­try un­der se­vere stress from the Covid-19 pan­demic, an eco­nomic crash and vi­o­lence in the streets over racist po­lice bru­tal­ity, the vol­ume of rhetoric about China is very high. There are wor­ries that this ex­ac­er­bates ten­sion in places such as the South China Sea or the Tai­wan Strait.</p>
    <p>A po­lit­i­cal risk an­a­lyst, who asked not to be named, tells The Sun­day Times: “If I were China’s for­eign pol­icy es­tab­lish­ment, I’d be get­ting ner­vous about ex­actly how far Trump plans to push the China bash­ing in the run-up to Novem­ber.”</p>
    <p>THE NEW WASH­ING­TON</p>
    <p>But while ac­knowl­edg­ing the risk, an­a­lysts do not see the Trump ad­min­is­tra­tion – or China – go­ing too far. “We urge all par­ties to ex­er­cise re­straint and not un­der­take mil­i­tary ac­tiv­i­ties that could threaten freedom of nav­i­ga­tion and ag­gra­vate dis­putes,” the US Depart­ment of De­fence said last Thurs­day in the wake of China’s bal­lis­tic mis­sile launches in the South China Sea.</p>
    <p>Dr Jack­son, who is also an ad­junct se­nior fel­low at the Cen­tre for a New Amer­i­can Se­cu­rity in Wash­ing­ton, wrote: “This is the new Wash­ing­ton, a place whose pol­i­tics on China leave Bi­den trapped be­tween Trump and</p>

